# Longest Common Subsequence

Given two strings $X$ and $Y$, the **longest common subsequence** (LCS) is the
longest sequence of characters that appears in both strings in the same
relative order (not necessarily contiguous). For $X = \text{"AGCT"}$ and
$Y = \text{"ACT"}$, the LCS is `"ACT"` (length 3).

Naïvely, there are $2^n$ possible subsequences — exponential. Dynamic
programming reduces this to $O(|X| \cdot |Y|)$ by filling a 2D table:

$$
dp[i][j] = \begin{cases}
  0 & \text{if } i = 0 \text{ or } j = 0 \\
  dp[i{-}1][j{-}1] + 1 & \text{if } X_i = Y_j \\
  \max(dp[i{-}1][j],\ dp[i][j{-}1]) & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

`dp[i][j]` is the LCS length of the first $i$ characters of $X$ and first $j$
characters of $Y$. The answer is `dp[|X|][|Y|]` — the bottom-right cell.

```python
def lcs(X, Y):
    m, n = len(X), len(Y)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if X[i - 1] == Y[j - 1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1])
    return dp[m][n]
```

