## Quiz

?? Why does the DP recurrence look at the diagonal cell `dp[i-1][j-1]` when characters match, but the top and left cells when they don't?
>> When $X_i = Y_j$, the match extends any LCS of the shorter prefixes — the relevant one is $dp[i-1][j-1]$ (both strings shortened by one), so the new LCS is that length plus one. When the characters don't match, the LCS of $X_{1..i}$ and $Y_{1..j}$ must come from either dropping $X_i$ (giving $dp[i-1][j]$) or dropping $Y_j$ (giving $dp[i][j-1]$); take the better of the two.

?? What's the time and space complexity of this algorithm?
>> Time: $O(m n)$ — each of the $m n$ cells takes constant work. Space: $O(m n)$ to store the full table. You can reduce space to $O(\min(m, n))$ if you only need the LCS length (keep the previous row), but reconstructing the actual subsequence needs the full table (or Hirschberg's algorithm).
